explanation:
To decide whether any operation in OS_TaskFindIdBySystemData is dead (i.e. can be removed without changing program behaviour) the analysis must know the semantics and side-effects of the calls, macros, constants and types used by the function:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: Macro may perform runtime checks, prints, or cause early return/abort. If it has side-effects (logging, error handling) its removal could change behaviour.
- OS_TaskValidateSystemData_Impl: Returned value and any side-effects (state changes, logging) determine whether the initial validation call is necessary; if it always returns OS_SUCCESS and has no side-effects it might be removable, otherwise not.
- OS_ObjectIdGetBySearch: Central search operation that controls whether the branch that assigns *task_id and calls release executes; need its contract (when it returns OS_SUCCESS, whether it has side-effects, whether it always uses the callback parameter).
- OS_TaskIdMatchSystemData_Impl: The callback used by OS_ObjectIdGetBySearch — its behaviour/side-effects determine whether the search does anything observable beyond returning a token (e.g. modifies global state).
- OS_ObjectIdFromToken: Extracts id from token; must know if it only reads token or also consumes/invalidates it — affects whether assignment to *task_id is necessary.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Releases token/transaction; may have important side-effects (unlocking, committing, resource free). Removing it could change program state even if return value unaffected.
- OS_object_token_t: Token representation and ownership rules (e.g. does it hold resources that must be freed via OS_ObjectIdRelease?). Type semantics are needed to judge whether release is dead.
- osal_id_t: Type/representation of task id to understand whether assigning *task_id has observable effects beyond storing a value (alignment/size/aliasing concerns).
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: The object type argument to the search — if this is a compile-time constant that makes the search a no-op, then related code may be dead; need its value/meaning.
- OS_SUCCESS: The success return code constant used in comparisons; must know possible return values and their meaning to determine which branches execute.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_GLOBAL: Locking mode passed to the search — if this forces particular transaction behaviour (or is a no-op), it affects whether release/transaction calls are required.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit / OS_ObjectIdFindNextMatch / OS_ObjectIdConvertToken / OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Internal callees of OS_ObjectIdGetBySearch. Their semantics (whether they alter global state, hold locks, or have other side-effects) are needed to judge whether calls into the search path or the subsequent release are removable.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish: Callee of OS_ObjectIdRelease — needed to know what release actually does (e.g. finish transaction, unlock). If finish has side-effects the release is not dead.
- OS_printf: Included because OS_CHECK_POINTER (or other validation code) may call it for diagnostics; printing is an observable effect and cannot be removed if present.

In short, to determine dead code one must know return-value contracts and side-effects (including locking/resource management and logging) of all called symbols, the ownership/lifetime rules for the token type, and the values/meanings of the constants passed. The symbols above are the minimal set required to make that determination for the target function.
